sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K315045
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: We created this part in an effort to determine how various lox sites interact.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This construct consists of a promoter followed by a "floxed" RFP gene. Because the two lox sites are not identical, we do not expect RFP to be excised when cre recombinase is introduced.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: pTet is a moderately strong promoter. RFP is a readily visible reporter.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Anvi Raina

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K315007
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: We learned about the use of variant lox sites to produce random fluorescent protein expression from the "Brainbow" paper (http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v450/n7166/full/nature06293.html).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The cre-lox system is used for site-specific recombination. Lox sites are 34 bp sequences of DNA that flank coding sequences. When cre recombinase is introduced, it can excise or invert the portions of DNA between two lox sites. If the two lox sites flanking the coding sequence are both forward or both reverse, the coding sequence will be excised, leaving one lox site behind. If one site is forward and the other reverse, the coding sequence will be inverted.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: In constructing variant lox sites, we looked for the least promiscuous sites - those that had the lowest rates of recombination with other variants.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Anvi Raina

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: RBS-RFP
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: RFP, BBa_E1010, with Elowitz RBS, BBa_B0034.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The part was needed for downstream applications. There can be no expression of a reporter without a ribosome binding site.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Kathy Lam, Danielle Nash

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: mRFP1
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: **highly** engineered mutant of red fluorescent protein from Discosoma striata (coral)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Campbell et al., PNAS v99 p7877 URL
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: monomeric RFP: Red Fluorescent Protein. Excitation peak: 584 nm Emission peak: 607 nm
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
TAATAA double stop codon added (DE).
Four silent mutations made to remove three EcoRI sites and one PstI site: A28G, A76G, A349G, G337A.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Drew Endy

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: p(tetR)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Lutz, R., Bujard, H., Nucleic Acids Research (1997) 25, 1203-1210.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Sequence for pTet inverting regulator driven by the TetR protein.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: BBa_R0040 TetR-Regulated Promoter is based on a cI promoter. It has been modified to include two TetR binding sites and the BioBrick standard assembly head and tail restriction sites.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: June Rhee, Connie Tao, Ty Thomson, Louis Waldman
